wadmiltilt: A strong rough woolen cloth employed to cover powder-barrels and to protect ammunition.

scrivello: An elephant's tusk of less than 20 pounds in weight.

scapulimancy: Divination by means of a shoulder-blade: same as omoplatoscopy.

queez-madam: The cuisse-madam, a French jargonelle pear.

progger: One who progs; a rambling or aimless searcher; specifically, one who progs for clams, oysters, etc., alongshore; a pot-fisherman.

piloerection: The erection of hairs or papillae.

furcatorium: The furciform bone, wishbone, or merrythought of a fowl: more fully called os furcatorium. See cut under furcula.

fungible: Returnable or negotiable in kind or by substitution, as a quantity of grain for an equal amount of the same kind of grain.

bum-clock: An insect which bums or hums, as a chafer or bee.

aglet: A tag or sheath, as of plastic, on the end of a lace, cord, or ribbon to facilitate its passing through eyelet holes.

aprosexia: Lack of power to keep the attention fixed on any subject; an extreme degree of mind-wandering.

snotter: To breathe through an obstruction in the nostrils; blubber; sob; cry.

widdershins: In a contrary or counterclockwise direction.

warkamoowee: A canoe with outriggers, used at Point de Galle, island of Ceylon.

dunga-runga: A small tree of crooked growth, Notelæa ovata, yielding close-grained, hard wood, used for tool-handles. See Notelæa.

zucchetta: In the Roman Catholic Church, the skullcap of an ecclesiastic, covering the tonsure. That of a priest is black, of a bishop purple, of a cardinal red, and of the Pope white. Also written zucchetto.

penistone: A coarse woolen stuff or frieze. It was in use in England during the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries. Also peniston, peneston, pennistone, pennystone, and forest whites.

rockhair: A rock-loving lichen, Alectoria jubata. See Alectoria.

fyrdung: In Anglo-Saxon history, the army prepared for war; a military expedition; a camp.

tantony: Same as Tantony pig; hence, a petted follower; a servile adherent.

jipijapa: A stemless palmlike plant (Carludovica palmata) of Central and South America, having long-stalked, fanlike leaves that are used to make Panama hats.

smuth: A miners'name for waste, poor, or small coal. See smut, 4.

glossanthrax: A disease in horses and cattle characterized by malignant carbuncles in the mouth, and especially on the tongue.

googwaruck: The mottled honey-eater or brush wattle-bird (A. carunculata) of Australia, a melliphagine bird of the genus Anthochœra.

woom: A trade-name for the fur of the beaver. There are four sorts—silvery, pale, white, and brown.

sexfoil: A plant or flower with six leaves.

baldachin: A rich fabric of silk and gold brocade.

androconia: Certain specialized scales oscurring in limited areas on the wings of the males of certain Lepidoptera.

anableps: A genus of cyprinodont fishes unique among vertebrates on account of the division of the cornea into upper and lower halves by a dark horizontal stripe of the conjunctiva, and the development of two pupils to each orbit, so that the fish appears to have four eyes, one pair looking upward and the other pair sidewise.

mehari: One of a race of swift Arabian camels taking name from Mehara, a region in Arabia where it is raised, and of great value in campaigning and in exploring expeditions.

zamouse: A West African buffalo, or bush-ox, found in Sierra Leone, Bos brachyceros, the short-horned buffalo, having the ears fringed with hair, short horns depressed at base, and no dewlap.

choil: To make a choil in (the blade of a knife).

miryachit: A neurosis observed in Siberia, characterized by extreme excitability and sometimes exhibitions of terror, with imitation of word and deed and often obscene speech.

furfur: An epidermal scale, as that associated with dandruff.

molebut: The short sunfish, a typical species of Molidæ, technically called Mola mola, M. rotunda, or Orthagoriscus mola. Also mole-bat. See cut at Mola.

bipennis: An ancient ax with two blades, one on each side of the handle.

hackmatack: Any of several North American trees, especially the tamarack.

yapok: An aquatic opossum (Chironectes minimus) of tropical regions of the Americas, having dense fur, webbed hind feet, and a long tail.

finochio: Fœniculum dulce, a variety of fennel; sweet fennel.

cisvestism: The wearing of clothing that does not represent one's profession or status

pungi: A Hindu pipe or nose-flute composed of a gourd or nut-shell into which two wooden pipes or reeds are inserted. It emits a droning or humming sound, and is the instrument commonly used by snake-charmers.

satrap: A governor of a province in ancient Persia.

silybum: A genus of thistles, belonging to the order Compositæ, tribe Cynaroideæ, and subtribe Carduineæ.

furfural: A colorless, sweet-smelling, oily liquid, C5H4O2, made from corncobs and other cellulosic wastes and used in the synthesis of furan derivatives, as a solvent for nitrocellulose, cellulose acetate, and certain dyes, and as a fungicide and insecticide.

cockchafer: Any of several large European scarab beetles of the genus Melolontha, especially M. melolontha, having larvae that damage plant roots and adults that feed on leaves.

zyzzyva: Any of several tropical American weevils of the genus Zyzzyva.

ginglymus: In anatomy, a hinge-joint or ginglymoid articulation; a diarthrodial joint permitting movement in one plane only, the result being simple flexion and extension.

sirgang: The so-called green jackdaw of Asia, Cissa sinensis.

biggin: A kind of coffee-pot containing a strainer for the infusion of the coffee, without allowing the grounds to mix with the infusion.

prunella: A strong heavy fabric of worsted twill, used chiefly for shoe uppers, clerical robes, and academic gowns.

hawsehole: An opening in the bow of a ship through which a cable or hawser is passed.

didunculus: A remarkable genus of pigeons, constituting the subfamily Didunculinœ of the family Columbidœ, or made the type of a different family, Didunculidœ.

haruspicy: Same as haruspication. Also aruspicy. See haruspex.

pogonophile: One who loves or studies beards.

gaster: The portion of the abdomen behind the petiole in ants and other hymenopterous insects.

swazzle: Device to change the voice to make it more raspy, used in Punch and Judy performances

scopula: A dense brushlike tuft of hairs, as on the feet of certain spiders and insects.

bunji-bunji: an Australian timber tree (Flindersia schottiana) whose bark yields a poison.

bogong: An Australian noctuid moth, Agrotis spina, which occurs in enormous numbers in Victoria, where the hibernating adults were eaten by the aborigines.

soushumber: A woolly and spiny species of nightshade, Solanum mammosum, of tropical America. It is a noxious weed, bearing worthless yellow inversely pear-shaped berries.

fiants: In hunting, the dung of the boar, wolf, fox, marten, or badger.

allocochick: The name of Indian shell-money used in northern California.

sarcology: The science of the soft or fleshy parts of the body: a department of anatomy distinguished from osteology.

coxopodite: In Arthropoda, as a crustacean, the proximal joint of a developed limb by which the limb articulates with its somite or segment of the body.

glabrescent: In botany, becoming glabrous, as organs that are hairy in the bud or young state and glabrous with age.

pipsissewa: Any of several evergreen plants of the genus Chimaphila in the heath family, especially C. umbellata, having white or pinkish flowers and formerly used as a medicinal herb.

gutta-percha: A rubbery substance derived from the latex of any of several tropical trees chiefly of the genus Palaquium of Southeast Asia, used in dental devices and formerly as an electrical insulator and in golf balls.

exophagy: A custom of certain cannibal tribes, prohibiting the eating of persons of their own tribe.

chiloma: In zoology, the upper lip or muzzle of a quadruped, when tumid and continued uninterruptedly from the nostril, as in the camel.

spong: A projection of land; an irregular, narrow, projecting part of a field.

carriwitchet: An absurd question; a quibble; a conundrum; a pun; a piece of jocularity or facetiousness.

jujuism: The system of beliefs and practices relating to the juju.

ranarium: A collection of live frogs; a place where frogs are kept alive, to study their transformations, for vivisection in physiological experiments, etc.

haptodysphoria: An odd sensation felt by certain people when handling peaches or other fuzzy surfaces.

wallwort: The dwarf elder, or danewort, Sambucus Ebulus; sometimes, also, the wall pellitory, Parietaria officinalis; the stonecrop, Sedum acre; and the navelwort, Cotyledon Umbilicus.

wonga-wonga: A large Australian pigeon, Lcucosarcia picata, having white flesh, and much esteemed for the table.

zugzwang: A situation in a chess game in which a player is forced to make an undesirable or disadvantageous move.

zumbooruk: A small cannon mounted on a swivel, usually shorter and with larger bore than the zingal.

sniggle: To fish for eels by thrusting a baited hook into their hiding places.

tzitzit: The knotted tassels of thread, symbolizing the 613 commandments in the Hebrew Scriptures, attached to the corners of a tallit or other garment.

fackeltanz: A torchlight procession, a survival from medieval tournaments, which is celebrated at some of the German courts on the marriage of a member of the royal family.

zufolo: A little flute or flageolet, especially such as is used in teaching birds.

tegestologist: someone who collects beer mats or coasters

hornito: A low mound of volcanic origin, sometimes emitting smoke or vapor.

bignonia: An evergreen woody vine (Bignonia capreolata) native to the southeast United States, having showy reddish orange trumpet-shaped flowers and stems that show a cross shape when cut in cross-section.

hectocotylus: A modified arm of the male of certain cephalopods, such as most octopuses, functioning as a reproductive organ in transferring sperm to the mantle cavity of the female.

slugga: In Ireland, a swallowhole, or abrupt deep cavity formed in certain limestone districts by the falling of parts of the surface-rock into depressions which have been made by subterranean rivers.

nurdle: To gently waffle or muse on a subject which one clearly knows little about.

shittah: A tree, probably a species of acacia, that was a source of a wood mentioned frequently in the Bible.

whizzer: A centrifugal machine used for drying sugar, grain, clothes, etc.

chitarrone: A large chitarra, usually with a double neck, much extended, very similar to that of the theorbo and archlute.

niblick: An iron-headed golf club with the face slanted at a greater angle than any other iron except a wedge; a nine iron.

cannelure: A groove around the cylinder of a bullet.

sniddle: Long coarse grass; sedges and allied plants of wet places. Halliwell; Britten and Holland, Eng. Plant Names.

scuppernong: A cultivated variety of the muscadine grape with sweet yellowish fruit.

morpunkee: A native pleasure-boat formerly much used for state occasions on the rivers of India.

pahoehoe: Lava with a smooth ropy surface.

schwenkfelder: A member of a German denomination founded in Silesia in the sixteenth century by Kaspar Schwenkfeld.

zobo: A breed of zebu-cattle, supposed to be a hybrid of the common zebu with the yak, reared in the western Himalayan region for its flesh and milk, and also as a beast of burden.

tarantism: A disorder characterized by an uncontrollable urge to dance, especially prevalent in southern Italy from the 15th to the 17th century and popularly attributed to the bite of a tarantula.

koomkie: A tame female elephant used as a decoy in the capture of wild male elephants.

extispicy: Divination by means of inspecting the entrails of sacrificed animals.

zarf: A chalicelike holder for a hot coffee cup, typically made of ornamented metal, used in the Middle East.

zenzizenzizenzic: the eighth power of a number

tacamahac: Any of several aromatic resinous substances used in ointments and incense.

acrocephalic: In ethnology, pertaining to or characterized by acrocephaly; high-skulled: as, acrocephalic men or tribes.

hypohippus: A genus of extinct perissodactyl ungulate mammals, of the family Anchitheriidæ

trocar: A sharp-pointed surgical instrument, used with a cannula to puncture a body cavity for fluid aspiration.

otolith: One of the small calcareous particles found in the inner ear of many vertebrates, especially fishes, which are involved in determining body orientation and sometimes in perceiving sound.

sialogogue: Producing a flow of saliva; ptyalogogue.

drapetomania: an overwhelming urge to run away (from home, a bad situation, responsibility, etc.)

bletting: The slow internal decay or “sleepiness” that takes place in some fruits, as apples and pears, after they are gathered.

paddlecock: The common lump-fish, Cyclopterus lumpus: so called in allusion to its dorsal ridge enveloped in tubercular skin, which resembles the comb of the domestic cock. See cut under Cyclopterus.

crizzle: To become wrinkled or rough on the surface, as glass, the skin, etc.

mamamouchi: A pompous title, from that supposed to have been conferred by the Sultan on M. Jourdain in Molière's play, ‘Le Bourgeois Gentilhomme’; hence, one who takes such a title; an ostentatious, self-important, and ridiculous pretender.

stadda: A doublebladed hand-saw, used for cutting comb-teeth. Also called steady.

oikofugic: Relating to or characterized by the desire to travel, migrate, play truant, etc.: opposed to oikotropic.

splanchnic: Of or relating to the viscera; visceral.

googol: The number 10 raised to the power 100 (10100), written out as the numeral 1 followed by 100 zeros.

lychnobite: One who labors at night and sleeps in the day.

fardingbag: The upper stomach of a cow.

furuncle: A circumscribed inflammation of the skin, forming a necrotic central core, and suppurating and discharging the core; a boil.

howdah: A seat, usually fitted with a canopy and railing, placed on the back of an elephant or a camel.

piblockto: In Greenland, a frenzied condition of dogs which results from continued exposure to extremely cold weather.

omphaloskepsis: Contemplation of or meditation upon one's navel.

philtrum: The groove running from the septum of the nose down the central line of the upper lip.

totipalmation: Complete palmation or full webbing of a bird's foot by three ample webs connecting all four toes, as of one of the Totipalmaæ: a leading character of that order of birds: correlated with palmation, 2, and semipalmation. See cuts under Phaëthon and totipalmate.

quipu: A cord about 2 feet in length, tightly spun from variously colored threads, and having a number of smaller threads attached to it in the form of a fringe: used among the ancient Peruvians and elsewhere for recording events, etc.

glossarium: In cntom., the long slender labrum of a mosquito or other predatory dipterous insect.

flews: The pendulous corners of the upper lip of certain dogs, such as the bloodhound.

ugli: A cross between a tangerine and grapefruit, grown in the West Indies.

tittup: To move in a lively, capering manner; prance.

slype: A covered passage, especially one between the transept and chapter house of a cathedral.

soogee-moogee: A type of strong cleaning product for wood and paint on board a boat.

sigogglin: not built correctly, crooked, skewed, out of balance.

piscatology: The scientific study of fishes; ichthyology.

thooid: Wolfish; resembling or related to the wolf; lupine: as, “the thoöid or lupine series” of canines, W. H. Flower.

fichu: A woman's triangular scarf of lightweight fabric, worn over the shoulders and crossed or tied in a loose knot at the breast.

carapace: A hard bony or chitinous outer covering, such as the fused dorsal plates of a turtle or the portion of the exoskeleton covering the head and thorax of a crustacean.

runtee: A disk of shell used as an ornament by the Indians of Virginia in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries.

kamalayka: A waterproof shirt made of intestines of seal or walrus.

ghurry: In India— A clepsydra, or water-instrument for measuring time.

galactophagist: One who eats or subsists on milk.

whickflaw: A swelling or inflammation about the nails or ends of the fingers; paronychia; whitlow. See whitlow.

bufagin: Any of a class of toxic steroids found in bufotoxin.

bissextile: Of or relating to a leap year.

bezoar: A hard indigestible mass of material, such as hair, plant fibers, or seeds, found in the stomach or intestine of animals, especially ruminants and sometimes humans. Bezoars were formerly considered to be antidotes to poisons and to possess magic properties.

baronduki: same as baranduki; the terrestrial Siberian squirrel.

natterjack: A very common European toad, Bufo calamita, belonging to the family Bufonidæ.

sortita: In music: The first air sung by any one of the principal singers in an opera; an entrance-air.

caruncle: A fleshy naked outgrowth, such as a fowl's wattles.

fipple: A whistlelike mouthpiece for certain wind instruments, such as a recorder or flageolet, that channels the breath toward the sounding edge of a side opening.

fartlek: An athletic training technique, used especially in running, in which periods of intense effort alternate with periods of less strenuous effort in a continuous workout.

gaffle: A portable fork of iron or wood in which the heavy musket formerly in use was rested that it might be accurately aimed and fired.

zoster: A belt or girdle worn by men in ancient Greece.

myomancy: A kind of divination or method of foretelling future events by the movements of mice.

ferdwit: In Anglo-Saxon law, a fine imposed on persons for not going forth in a military expedition.

glendoveer: In Southey's poem. “The Curse of Kehama” (1810), one of a race of beautiful sprites. Glenoid notch.See notch.

fud: The scut or tail of the hare, cony, etc.

fumet: The dung of the deer, hare, etc.

floripondio: A plant, the Datura sanguinea, an infusion from whose seeds, prepared by the Peruvians, induces stupefaction, and, if much used, furious delirium.

schemozzle: (Yiddish) a confused situation or affair; a mess

twankay: A brand of green tea grown and prepared in the western part of the province of Chĕ-kiang, China.

deasil: Motion according to the apparent course of the sun. See withershins.

swallet: Water breaking in upon the miners at their work; -- so called among tin miners.

kakkerlak: A cockroach. Cassell, Nat. Hist., VI. 132.

musnud: In India, a raised seat, overspread with carpets or embroidered cloth and furnished with pillows for the back and elbow.

doromania: An unusual urge or preoccupation with giving gifts.

pogonip: A frozen fog, formed in the coldest weather in the mountain valleys of Idaho, Nevada, and Colorado. When inhaled it often produces severe pulmonary trouble.

oogonium: Any of the cells that give rise through mitosis to the oocytes and are found in the ovaries of vertebrates.

decussated: Simple past tense and past participle of decussate.

emunction: The act of blowing one's nose.
